What a nice little surprise. A sweet, little ramen shop. They maybe have 4-5 tables, only one table for 4. The kuu chili and spicy tonkontsu both had amazing broths and meat to offer. I would say we prefer the Kuu more, only because it was actually spicy. The tonkotsu was a touch salty but I’m a little sensitive to salt. I had a side of the chili oil which has a ton of sesame flavor and was very good. Tuna tartare was our appetizer of choice. Fresh and delicious, the avocado was an excellent addition. Service was very quick and polite. Eating and leaving is appreciated here as they need the table space.

The prices are fair for a ramen shop in Manhattan. It’s delicious and I will be a returning customer!

First off I'm not a huge fan of paying what I'd like to call the ramen multiples. 15$ for a noodle soup in my mind is just way more than it should cost. Therefore I made the GF pay for this meal 😁. In NYC there are so many ramen places so I'm writing this from a perspective of everyday ramen versus that unique special ramen that I will remember forever. Place is small, service is fast. The noodle quality is decent. I got the tonkasu shoyu which is awesome because it comes with the egg. Soup base was good; not overly salty and you can tell it wasn't watered down etc. The pork pieces were nice size. Other places (other fancier places) have slice them extremely thin...I'm not a fan of that. They essentially make you order extra which is another 4$. Which leads to my point of expensive multiples. This place doesn't do that which is great

Good ramen. I had the Kuu Chili Ramen. Broth was excellent. Noodles were quite thin; would’ve preferred thicker noodles. All the ingredients meshed quite nicely together.  Complaints. It’s dark in there. It was hard to see almost anything. They could at least turn the lights up a bit. I went at 7:30 pm on a Friday, and there was a short wait. A lot of people usually means it’s a good place, but that’s not the problem. The place is too damn small. They only have like 3 tables that hold around 6 people each and two bar-like areas that hold 2-4 each. That’s not enough for a ramen place. It was super cramped, and I was seated awkwardly between a group of 3 people and a couple. It was super obvious that they were trying to herd you out asap because people were waiting for you to finish.  Lastly, prices were high. I paid $18 for that one bowl of ramen. Not as expensive as some other ramen places (ahem, Ichiran...), but still on the high side. Good taste, bad seating and environment. Maybe come at an hour that isn’t lunch or dinner-time, say 3 or 4 pm.

Legit Japanese style ramen with good noodles and broth, delicious soft roast pork, and very decent soft boiled ramen eggs. Portions are about right, maybe slightly smaller bowls with slightly less broth than some other NYC spots, but that's ok. The amount of food is plentiful. Lots of good menu options with plenty of different toppings in one selection, and a good amount of each. I've had the spicy one (not Kuu Chili Chili, the other spicy one) which was good but not super spicy, and the Okinawa Shio Ramen. Would get both again. The kara age fried chicken is pretty good, not mind-blowing, but worth getting to share.  Service is very fast after ordering, as everything is basically already ready and just needs to be assembled. At lunch it seems like you wait and collect your own order on trays because it's too busy for table service, but at dinner we were served at our table. We had a wait to sit and a wait to order at lunch, but it wasn't too bad, maybe 5-10 minutes.  Seating is limited with all high-top 6-seat communal tables and some high bar seating on the wall and in the front window. That said, even with groups of 6 people at prime times (lunch and dinner) we've been able to sit together after some earlier folks finished eating. Staff is accommodating of people changing seats and the patrons are generally understanding and considerate, and don't linger unnecessarily if there is a group that's split up and waiting for adjacent seats.  Will definitely be coming here more in the fall and winter for comfort food.
